{% submission %}

{% submission-part type="problem" %}

Currently, the educational technology landscape is deeply bifurcated. High-quality, data-driven platforms often reside behind expensive paywalls, creating an "achievement gap" based on a school’s or family's ability to pay. Conversely, free alternatives frequently rely on unmonitored advertisements or "gamified" loops that prioritize entertainment over meaningful cognitive engagement. This leaves a significant void: there is no unified, accessible "one-stop shop" capable of providing rigorous, individualized instruction across core subjects like math, reading, and writing (including phonics) without compromising the student's focus or the district's budget.

{% /submission-part %}

{% submission-part type="proposed-solution" %}

The remedy lies in a platform designed around adaptive mastery. Rather than a static repository of videos or games, the technology should begin with a diagnostic assessment mapped directly to state or national learning standards. By identifying specific fundamental gaps, the system can automatically curate a personalized learning path that "meets the student where they are." As the student demonstrates proficiency, the platform should dynamically adjust in real-time—advancing the complexity of the material or pivoting to reinforce prerequisite skills as needed. This ensures that the technology acts as a responsive tutor, constantly recalibrating to keep the student in the "zone of proximal development."

{% /submission-part %}

{% /submission %}